DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain encompasses the major philosophical theories of linguistic meaning
and reference. The central debate concerns how expressions acquire meaning:
through reference to objects in the world (referentialism/denotationalism),
through descriptive content associated with expressions (descriptivism), through
inferential relations between expressions (inferentialism), or through use in
language games (use theories). The Kripke-Putnam revolution in the 1970s
established direct reference theory and semantic externalism as dominant
positions, challenging Fregean descriptivism. Recent decades have seen renewed
interest in inferentialist alternatives (Brandom) and two-dimensional semantics
(Chalmers) that attempt to reconcile referentialist insights with the role of
conceptual content. Metasemantics—theories about what facts ground meaning—has
emerged as a distinct field examining whether meaning is fixed by causal-
historical chains, community practices, functional roles, or normative
inferential patterns.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The symbol grounding problem presupposes that symbols require "grounding" in
non-symbolic reality—a claim that makes most sense within referentialist/
denotational frameworks where meaning is fundamentally about word-world
relations. Alternative theories (inferentialism, use theories, conceptual role
semantics) suggest meaning might be constituted by intralinguistic relations,
making the grounding problem appear theoretically parochial rather than
universal. This domain provides the theoretical apparatus to assess whether
SGP implicitly assumes one metasemantic view and whether it dissolves under
alternative frameworks.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The connection between theories of meaning and the symbol grounding problem
remains underexplored in philosophy of language. Few papers explicitly examine
how different metasemantic theories bear on grounding requirements for AI
systems. The literature would benefit from work examining whether inferentialist
or use-theoretic frameworks make the SGP disappear or transform it into a
different kind of problem.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Organize the synthesis around competing metasemantic visions: (1) referentialist
views that make grounding central, (2) descriptivist views where grounding is
mediated by sense, (3) inferentialist views where meaning is role in reasoning,
(4) use theories where meaning is practice-embedded. Show how each framework
would diagnose the SGP differently. Recent metasemantics literature (Speaks,
Burgess-Sherman) provides tools for this comparison.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Direct Reference/Causal Theories: 8 papers - Kripke, Donnellan, Devitt establish that proper names and natural kind terms refer directly via causal-historical chains, not descriptive content
- Inferentialism: 6 papers - Brandom, Peregrin, Hlobil argue meaning is constituted by inferential role in reasoning practices
- Two-Dimensional Semantics: 2 papers - Chalmers attempts to reconcile Kripkean insights with role of conceptual content
- Metasemantics: 4 papers - Recent work on what grounds meaning facts (externalism, conceptual role, normative patterns)
====================================================================
}

