DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Meta-semantics investigates what makes semantic facts obtain—the foundations
of meaning itself. It asks: in virtue of what do expressions have the semantic
contents they do? This domain is distinct from first-order semantics (which
specifies what expressions mean) and addresses the grounding question of what
determines those meanings. Major positions include: use-based accounts (meaning
grounded in linguistic practice), causal-historical theories (reference fixed
by causal chains), teleosemantic views (meaning grounded in biological function),
interpretationist approaches (meaning determined by interpretation), and
reference magnetism (naturalness constrains reference). Recent work has
increasingly questioned idealized assumptions in traditional meta-semantics,
exploring non-ideal foundations that account for power, diversity of goals,
and social position. The field has also seen growth in conceptual engineering—
the normative project of revising concepts—which raises meta-semantic questions
about the feasibility and mechanisms of semantic change.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is central to evaluating whether the symbol grounding problem (SGP)
presupposes a narrow meta-semantic view. If the SGP assumes denotational or
referential semantics must be grounded in a particular way, examining the full
landscape of meta-semantic positions reveals whether that assumption is
warranted. The recent emphasis on non-ideal foundations and use-based accounts
provides alternatives to purely referential approaches, potentially dissolving
or reframing the grounding problem.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
Relatively few papers directly connect meta-semantic theory to the symbol
grounding problem as formulated in AI/cognitive science. Most meta-semantic
work focuses on natural language rather than formal or artificial symbol
systems. The interaction between meta-semantics and embodied/grounded cognition
remains under-explored philosophically.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Pay attention to the distinction between semantic theories (which specify
meanings) and meta-semantic theories (which explain what grounds those meanings).
Consider whether different meta-semantic positions would diagnose the SGP
differently—some might see it as a pseudo-problem arising from false meta-
semantic assumptions. The recent turn toward non-ideal and pragmatic foundations
may offer resources for reframing grounding concerns.

